15\. Our loves in life are of every kind. One man longs to have
nobility, another cares nothing for this, but wishes to be called the
master of many possessions in his halls. Another is pleased to speak
what is utterly unsound from his mind and to persuade his neighbours
with wicked boldness. Others seek shameful gains from mortals rather
than honour. But I wish to win none of these: I would choose to have a
reputation of fair fame.

