16\. (*Aeacus in Hades, to Heracles*): Ha, what is this? I see someone
hurrying thither with confident mind. Tell me truly, stranger, who are
you who approach these regions, and for what reason?

(*Heracles replies*): I have no hesitation in disclosing the whole tale.
My native land is Argos, my name is Heracles, I am the son of Zeus,
father of all the gods; for Zeus came to my mother's marriage-bed, as is
said in truth. I come here perforce, obeying the commands of Eurystheus,
who sent me to fetch the hound of hell alive to the gates of Mycenae,
and he thought that in this he had invented a task impossible for

<span id="page_157">p. 157</span>

me to fulfil. On this quest I have travelled round to the remote regions
of all Europe and Asia.

17\. (*Mention of the Plêmochoê, earthenware vessel used on the last day
of the Eleusinian Mysteries*).

*Chorus:* In order that we may pour forth these vessels into the earthy
chasm.

